  'second century AD, the Roman container takes the shape of divine hero Hercules, instantly '
  'recognizable for the lion skin wrapped around his torso. Its iconography suggests that it was '
  'almost certainly used by an athlete or fighter; statues of Hermes and Hercules were common '
  'accoutrements in gymnasia through to the Roman period. Even in antiquity, athletes often used '
  'ointments and oils after practice or competitions, and so such masculine subjects were an '
