  'indispensable element of French cuisine. Used for squeezing the juices out of a duck carcass in '
  'preparing the traditional dish canard au sang, this screw-type appliance was both efficient and '
  'easy to use. The cast metal frame, fabulously standing on two duck feet, was meant to be '
  'secured to a work surface, and with the double-latched silver-plate container, was built to '
  'last. At one time, no respectable French restaurant would be without one of these grand '
  'devices, but today, even new presses are hard to find outside of the finest establishment. An '
