  'century’s greatest champion and chronicler of rural America, and he always aimed to capture the '
  'rich diversity of the country’s landscape, from the vast farming fields of the Midwest to the '
  'dense forests of the East Coast. Among his many inspirations, still lifes were a common thread '
  'across his oeuvre, and The Lost Penny is a striking example of the artist’s distinctive '
  'aesthetic. In this wild still life by Benton, an expertly rendered tangle of foliage sits '
  'against a backdrop of rocks and a tree trunk in an impressive study of texture and detail. A '
  'single shiny penny rests on a gray rock almost hidden amid the weeds, encouraging examination '
