  "referred to as Moretto or Moor's head, have been used in heraldry, jewelry, and the decorative "
  'arts for centuries. The forms represent the historic emblem of Venice, dating from the medieval '
  'period, when Saracen pirates plagued the coast of Dalmatia. Their use in decorating interiors '
  'spread quickly to the royal courts of Europe, where they were considered exotic symbols of '
  'wealth, luxury and good fortune. The popularity of blackamoors soon spread to the European '
  'aristocracy, who commissioned beautiful figures such as the current examples as a way to bring '
  'courtly fashion into their homes. Seldom do original pairs of marble blackamoors come on the '
