  'iron and is designed to be virtually unbreakable. Also called an Armada chest, the box features '
  'an imposing iron strapwork motif. A false keyhole surrounded by open-work escutcheon at the '
  'front is flanked by two padlock rings, increasing the appearance of impregnability. The real '
  'lock, however, is hidden in the top of the lid in the strapwork design. Upon opening, the '
  'sophisticated mechanics, which consist of seven latches, remains concealed behind an ornately '
  'pierced shield with mirrored, finely engraved mermaids. The interior also features two levels '
  'of safety, with a separate, lockable interior compartment on the left side. Although made '
  'primarily in southern Germany, especially Nuremburg, in the 16th and 17th centuries, these '
